- A. Censi, [Gian Diego Tipaldi][tipaldi] "*Lazy localization using a Frozen-Time Filter*", submitted to ICRA'08. 

  - [draft version (PDF)](http://purl.org/censi/research/2008-icra-ftf-draft.pdf)

**Abstract** --  One of the open problems of SLAM (Simultaneous Localization and Mapping) research is loop closure.  In this paper, we model loop closure as a smoothing  problem  ("lazy" localization) instead of filtering (global localization).  
We present a new algorithm for solving the lazy localization problem called Frozen-Time Filter (FTF). Time is 'frozen', in the sense that the belief always refers to the same time instant, instead of following a moving target, like Monte Carlo Localization does.  
The Frozen-Time Filter exploits the fact that, during a SLAM process, a quite precise estimate of the incremental motion of the robot is usually available. Under the same assumption, we design two Monte  Carlo methods for lazy localization. The experiments suggest that a naive implementation of FTF is more efficient than a extremely optimized equivalent Monte Carlo solution. Moreover, the grid representation used by FTF solves some of the annoying problems of particle filters.


